Locations (LOC) extension extends the [[[DPV]]] to provide additional concepts regarding locations such as countries and regions. The canonical URL for LOC is https://w3id.org/dpv/loc, the namespace is https://w3id.org/dpv/loc#, the suggested prefix is loc, and this document along with source and releases are available at https://github.com/w3c/dpv.

DRAFT RELEASE This is draft release intended for review.

DPV Specifications: The [[DPV]] is the core specification within the DPV family, with the following extensions: Personal Data [[PD]], Locations [[LOC]], Risk Management [[RISK]], Technology [[TECH]] and [[AI]], [[JUSTIFICATIONS]], [[SECTOR]] specific extensions, and [[LEGAL]] extensions modelling specific jurisdictions and regulations. A [[PRIMER]] introduces the concepts and modelling of DPV specifications, and [[GUIDES]] describe application of DPV for specific applications and use-cases. The Search Index page provides a searchable hierarchy of all concepts. The Data Privacy Vocabularies and Controls Community Group (DPVCG) develops and manages these specifications through GitHub. For meetings, see the DPVCG calendar.

To cite and understand the structure of DPV, the article "Data Privacy Vocabulary (DPV) - Version 2.0" (2024) describes the current state of DPV and extensions from version 2.0 onwards (open access version here). The earlier article "Creating A Vocabulary for Data Privacy" (2019) describes how the DPV was developed (open access versions here, here, and here).

Contributing: The DPVCG welcomes participation to improve the DPV and associated resources, including expansion or refinement of concepts, requesting information and applications, and addressing open issues. See contributing guide for further information.

Introduction

The Locations ([[LOC]]) extension extends the [[DPV]] to provide concepts representing locations based on the ISO 3166 and UN M49 standards. At the moment, it provides country codes and regions with plans for future iterations to provide additional concepts representing provinces and cities. In addition to ISO 3166 countries and subdivisions, the extension also provides a representation of geo-political supra-unions such as the EU with a list of its member countries. Through these concepts, the [[LOC]] extension enables representation and use of locations with other DPV concepts, such as to indicate where the data is being stored or processed, or to indicate the data subjects are from a particular location.

ISO and UN taxonomies

To express the ISO and UN codes for specific locations, the following properties have been introduced:

  1. [=iso_alpha2=] to represent the 2-letter ISO 3166 alpha2 codes
  2. [=iso_alpha3=] to represent the 3-letter ISO 3166 alpha3 codes
  3. [=iso_numeric=] to represent the ISO 3166 numeric codes
  4. [=un_m49=] to represent the 2-letter UN M49 codes

In addition to these, the country table further in the document also contains links to the ISO Online Browsing Platform (OBP) and the EU Vocabularies.

Locations as Jurisdictions

The [[[LEGAL]]] extensions use these concepts to represent jurisdictions, and to associate laws and authorities with their specific geo-political entities. To further support the legal/jurisdictional use of locations, the extension also defines the InverseJurisdiction concept which represents a list of all other jurisdictions for a given location. This helps in defining information and constraints such as "data transfers outside of XYZ location". To implement this, the extension defines a `non-XYZ` concept for each `XYZ` (currently limited to countries and supranational unions), and then associates all jurisdictions which are not `XYZ` with the concept `non-XYZ` using the SKOS narrower/broader relations. The association between `XYZ` and `non-XYZ` is unidirectional and is specified using through the relation hasInverseJurisdiction , i.e. we only state `non-XYZ` is the inverse set of jurisdictions for `XYZ` and do not state `XYZ` is the inverse of `non-XYZ` to avoid circular or recursive associations in resolving jurisdictions.

Country IRIs are defined by their ISO 3166-1 Alpha2 codes in the following format: https://w3id.org/dpv/loc#<code>. The inverse for each country is defined by prefixing the country code with non- which gives the IRI https://w3id.org/dpv/loc#non-<code>. The inverse jurisdiction is defined as a set containing all other countries that are not the target country, associated using skos:narrower relations.

The example shows the definition of Ireland as a location and its inverse jurisdictional concept.

loc:IE a dpv:Country ;
  dpv:hasInverseJurisdiction loc:non-IE .

loc:non-IE a dpv:InverseJurisdiction ;
  skos:narrower loc:AD ;
                # countries except loc:IE
                loc:ZW .

Unions and Memberships

To express unions and memberships such as for [=EEA=] and [=EU=], the [[SKOS]] relations narrower/broader are used, with the union expressed as an instance of dpv:SupraNationalUnion.

Unions and Memberships

EEA - European Economic Area (EEA)

Concept representing the latest membership of European Economic Area (EEA).

The following countries are members of this union: Austria (AT), Belgium (BE), Bulgaria (BG), Cyprus (CY), Czechia (CZ), Germany (DE), Denmark (DK), Estonia (EE), Spain (ES), Finland (FI), France (FR), Greece (GR), Croatia (HR), Hungary (HU), Ireland (IE), Iceland (IS), Italy (IT), Liechtenstein (LI), Lithuania (LT), Luxembourg (LU), Latvia (LV), Malta (MT), Netherlands (NL), Norway (NO), Poland (PL), Portugal (PT), Romania (RO), Sweden (SE), Slovenia (SI), Slovakia (SK)

EEA30 - EEA 30 Member States

Concept represent current EEA with 30 Member States that became active from 2020 with exit of UK from EEA31 after Brexit.

The following countries are members of this union: Austria (AT), Belgium (BE), Bulgaria (BG), Cyprus (CY), Czechia (CZ), Germany (DE), Denmark (DK), Estonia (EE), Spain (ES), Finland (FI), France (FR), Greece (GR), Croatia (HR), Hungary (HU), Ireland (IE), Iceland (IS), Italy (IT), Liechtenstein (LI), Lithuania (LT), Luxembourg (LU), Latvia (LV), Malta (MT), Netherlands (NL), Norway (NO), Poland (PL), Portugal (PT), Romania (RO), Sweden (SE), Slovenia (SI), Slovakia (SK)

EEA31 - EEA 31 Member States

Concept representing previous EEA with 31 Member States that was active from 2014 and concluded with the exit of UK in 2022 after Brexit.

The following countries are members of this union: Austria (AT), Belgium (BE), Bulgaria (BG), Cyprus (CY), Czechia (CZ), Germany (DE), Denmark (DK), Estonia (EE), Spain (ES), Finland (FI), France (FR), United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (GB), Greece (GR), Croatia (HR), Hungary (HU), Ireland (IE), Iceland (IS), Italy (IT), Liechtenstein (LI), Lithuania (LT), Luxembourg (LU), Latvia (LV), Malta (MT), Netherlands (NL), Norway (NO), Poland (PL), Portugal (PT), Romania (RO), Sweden (SE), Slovenia (SI), Slovakia (SK)

EU - European Union (EU)

Concept representing the latest membership of European Union (EU).

The following countries are members of this union: Austria (AT), Belgium (BE), Bulgaria (BG), Cyprus (CY), Czechia (CZ), Germany (DE), Denmark (DK), Estonia (EE), Spain (ES), Finland (FI), France (FR), Greece (GR), Croatia (HR), Hungary (HU), Ireland (IE), Italy (IT), Lithuania (LT), Luxembourg (LU), Latvia (LV), Malta (MT), Netherlands (NL), Poland (PL), Portugal (PT), Romania (RO), Sweden (SE), Slovenia (SI), Slovakia (SK)

EU27 - EU 27 Member States

Concept representing current EU with 27 Member States that became active from 2020 with exit of UK from EEA31 after Brexit.

The following countries are members of this union: Austria (AT), Belgium (BE), Bulgaria (BG), Cyprus (CY), Czechia (CZ), Germany (DE), Denmark (DK), Estonia (EE), Spain (ES), Finland (FI), France (FR), Greece (GR), Croatia (HR), Hungary (HU), Ireland (IE), Italy (IT), Lithuania (LT), Luxembourg (LU), Latvia (LV), Malta (MT), Netherlands (NL), Poland (PL), Portugal (PT), Romania (RO), Sweden (SE), Slovenia (SI), Slovakia (SK)

EU28 - EU 28 Member States

Concept representing previous EEA with 31 Member States that was active from 2014 and concluded with the exit of UK in 2022 after Brexit.

The following countries are members of this union: Austria (AT), Belgium (BE), Bulgaria (BG), Cyprus (CY), Czechia (CZ), Germany (DE), Denmark (DK), Estonia (EE), Spain (ES), Finland (FI), France (FR), United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (GB), Greece (GR), Croatia (HR), Hungary (HU), Ireland (IE), Italy (IT), Lithuania (LT), Luxembourg (LU), Latvia (LV), Malta (MT), Netherlands (NL), Poland (PL), Portugal (PT), Romania (RO), Sweden (SE), Slovenia (SI), Slovakia (SK)

Funding Sponsors

The DPVCG was established as part of the SPECIAL H2020 Project, which received funding from the European Union’s Horizon 2020 research and innovation programme under grant agreement No. 731601 from 2017 to 2019.

Harshvardhan J. Pandit was funded to work on DPV from 2020 to 2022 by the Irish Research Council's Government of Ireland Postdoctoral Fellowship Grant#GOIPD/2020/790.

The ADAPT SFI Centre for Digital Media Technology is funded by Science Foundation Ireland through the SFI Research Centres Programme and is co-funded under the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) through Grant#13/RC/2106 (2018 to 2020) and Grant#13/RC/2106_P2 (2021 onwards).

Funding Acknowledgements for Contributors

The contributions of Harshvardhan J. Pandit have been made with the financial support of Science Foundation Ireland under Grant Agreement No. 13/RC/2106_P2 at the ADAPT SFI Research Centre.
